                <h3><a
                    href="https://edition.cnn.com/2020/06/28/weather/hurricane-season-florida-coronavirus-power-companies/index.html"
                    target="_blank">The
                    pandemic could lead to longer power outages following a hurricane</a></h3>
                <p>Power companies across hurricane-prone states are forced to face a prospect they've never dealt with
                  before: restoring power after a major storm amid a global pandemic.Long restoration times are likely
                  depending on how the coronavirus plays out during the six-month
                  Atlantic hurricane season, which started June 1 and is predicted to be extremely active.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-4">
              <div class="news">
                <div class="date">Jul 21</div>
                <h3><a
                    href="https://edition.cnn.com/2020/07/18/weather/fewer-flights-covid-weather-forecast-hurricane-impact/index.html"
                    target="_blank">Weather forecasts are less accurate because of Covid-19</a></h3>
                <p>As the US heads into peak hurricane season, a reduction in commercial airline
                  flights due to Covid-19 has significantly impacted our ability to accurately forecast the weather.A
                  study out this week by Dr. Ying Chen, a senior research associate at Lancaster University's
                  Environment Centre, highlights this problem (Covid-19).</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-4">
              <div class="news">
                <div class="date">Jul 21</div>
                <h3><a
